In [[metaphysics]], '''haecceitism''' is the perspective implied by the belief that [[entities]] can have [[haecceity]] or individual essence, "a set of principles which are essential to it and distinguish it from everything else."<ref>Read, Stephen (1995). ''Thinking About Logic'', Oxford UP, p. 249. {{ISBN|019289238X}}.</ref> [[James Ladyman]] characterizes haecceitism as "the claim that worlds can differ ''solo numero'', that worlds can differ ''[[de re and de dicto|de re]]'' whilst not differing ''[[de re and de dicto|de dicto]]'', sometimes said, that worlds can differ solely by the [[permutation]] of [[individuals]]."<ref>Ladyman, James (2012). [http://podcasts.ox.ac.uk/identity-individuality-and-discernibility-audio Identity, Individuality and Discernibility]. University of Oxford Podcasts.</ref>

